Rating: 4
All lasagne is time consuming, this isn't difficult at all. Some hints: Half the squash and then microwave it on high for 1 minute - that makes it easier to cut. Cut in quarters, remove seeds, cut deep slahes in the flesh. Put on aluminum foiled baking sheet, flesh side up. Toss a peeled quarterd onion and 3 unpeeled cloves of garlic with 1 tsp oil and add to squash, onion, cut side down. Bake 45 to 60 minutes or until soft. The hardest part is waiting for the squash to cool so you can handle it. While the squash is cooking stick the hazelnuts in the oven for 4-5 minubtes. Then put them in a clean dish cloth and rub well - most of the skins will come off. Chop the nuts in a small cuisinart and use the same machine to chop the onion and garlic(pressed out of skin). This is an oustanding recipe - it is very light so does only serve six. As others said, do increase the salt and sage.

Rating: 4
Okay, I admit it ... I was a sceptic about squash and nuts in lasagna. But this! This is amazing!! Having read many of the reviews first, I decided increased the onion and garlic many-fold, then roasted the squash, onions and garlic with a little olive oil. Excellent suggestions, everyone! I did use the hazelnuts, but ground them up to incorporate better in the mix, which turned out extremely well. Absolutely use fresh sage for this dish. For all the effort (and it was time-consuming), this is well worth it. Hubby loved it - I will definitely make this again and again. Thanks!

