What is no boil lasagna? Do I cook the noodles first?

Rating: 4
This recipe took a little longer, but there are some shortcuts that eliminate the hard work. First, buy packaged hazelnuts that are already chopped. I found them in the baking section at the supermarket with the other nuts. I just spread them out on a tray and toasted them lightly in the toaster oven. Next, buy pre-peeled and cored butternut squash. I found this in the produce section sealed in plastic. All you have to do is chop it up. The rest of the tasks are pretty manageable and the lasagne is delicious.

Rating: 2
Next time, I'd make extra sauce--the top layer of lasagna didn't quite have enough liquid to soak up. Also, use more cheese. It takes a long time to cut up the squash...good but not quite worth the effort.

Rating: 0
I just completed this very time consuming recipe for dinner tonight. Since I haven't eaten it yet, I can't rate how many forks it should have, but our daughter made it and raved about it. So I am sure that we will love it. She said that the hazelnuts were difficult to work with and the skins didn't all come off, so I told her to use pinenuts next time. I like their flavor better anyway. That is what I did, and I put them in with the onions when I sauteed them. The squash is another matter. I cut it in quarters and baked it thinking that it would be easy to scoop out, but it took a long time to do. It was still too firm to scoop. Next time I would probably just peel it as directed, cook it a little longer, and mash it slightly. My other suggestion would be to get the food processor out and use it for the onion, sage, and cheese to cut down on prep time. The fresh mozzarella was hard to grate by hand.

Rating: 3
A lot of work but worth it. Next time will use pecans and cut the squash in smaller pieces.

Rating: 4
